UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# How the Internet Works\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nEvery time you visit a website, open an app, or send a message, data travels through a vast global network at the speed of light. That network — the **internet** — is the invisible backbone of the digital world.\n\nUnderstanding how the internet works is the **first superpower of every web developer**. It tells you why pages sometimes load slowly, why HTTPS matters, and how your code actually reaches users.\n\n> **Real-world relevance:** At companies like Zomato, Swiggy, and Razorpay, engineers constantly think about network latency, DNS configuration, and CDN placement. This knowledge directly impacts app speed and user experience.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this lesson you will be able to:\n- Explain what the internet is and how it differs from the World Wide Web\n- Describe the client-server model with a real example\n- Trace the journey of a URL request from browser to server and back\n- Explain what IP addresses, DNS, HTTP, and HTTPS are\n- Understand TCP/IP and why it matters\n- Identify performance bottlenecks caused by network factors\n\n---\n\n## 3. Concept Explanation\n\n### Beginner Level — What is the Internet?\n\nThe internet is a **global network of computers** connected together through cables, fibre optics, satellites, and wireless signals.\n\nThink of it like a massive postal system:\n- Every device has a unique address (IP address)\n- Data is split into small packets (like envelopes)\n- Packets travel through routers (like post offices)\n- They reassemble at the destination\n\nThe **World Wide Web (WWW)** is NOT the internet — it is a SERVICE that runs ON the internet. Email, WhatsApp, online gaming — these also run on the internet but are not the web.\n\n```\nThe Internet = Road Network\nThe Web      = All the shops/buildings accessible via those roads\nEmail        = Courier service using those roads\nFTP          = File transport using those roads\n```\n\n### Intermediate Level — The Client-Server Model\n\nEvery web interaction involves two parties:\n\n| Role | Description | Example |\n|------|-------------|--------|\n| **Client** | The device making the request | Your browser (Chrome, Firefox) |\n| **Server** | The machine responding to requests | A computer hosting rlearn.com |\n\nWhen you visit `rlearn.com`:\n1. Your browser (client) sends a **request** to the server\n2. The server processes it and sends a **response** back\n3. Your browser renders the HTML into a visible page\n\n### Advanced Level — The Full Request Journey\n\nHere is exactly what happens when you type `https://rlearn.com` and press Enter:\n\n```\nStep 1: DNS Resolution\n  Browser checks local cache → OS cache → Router cache → ISP DNS Server\n  DNS returns: rlearn.com → 104.21.45.67\n\nStep 2: TCP Handshake (SYN → SYN-ACK → ACK)\n  Client: "I want to connect" (SYN)\n  Server: "OK, I''m ready" (SYN-ACK)\n  Client: "Great, let''s go" (ACK)\n\nStep 3: TLS Handshake (for HTTPS)\n  Exchange encryption keys\n  Establish secure channel\n\nStep 4: HTTP Request\n  Browser sends: GET / HTTP/1.1\n                 Host: rlearn.com\n                 Accept: text/html\n\nStep 5: Server Processing\n  Loads HTML, CSS, JS, images\n\nStep 6: HTTP Response\n  Server sends: HTTP/1.1 200 OK\n                Content-Type: text/html\n                [HTML content...]\n\nStep 7: Browser Rendering\n  Parse HTML → Build DOM\n  Parse CSS  → Build CSSOM\n  Execute JS → Manipulate DOM\n  Paint → Display page\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Visual Learning\n\n```\n                    YOU\n                     |\n               [Your Browser]\n                     |\n              [Your Router]\n                     |\n          [ISP (Internet Service Provider)]\n                     |\n            [Internet Backbone]\n                     |\n             [CDN Edge Server]        ← Static files cached here\n                     |\n          [Load Balancer]             ← Distributes traffic\n                /    \\\n          [Server 1] [Server 2]       ← Application servers\n                |         |\n           [Database]  [Cache]        ← Data layer\n\n\n DNS Resolution:\n  Browser → DNS Resolver → Root NS → TLD NS → Authoritative NS → IP\n\n\n TCP/IP Stack:\n  Application Layer  → HTTP, HTTPS, FTP, SMTP\n  Transport Layer    → TCP, UDP\n  Internet Layer     → IP, ICMP\n  Network Layer      → Ethernet, WiFi\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Syntax / Protocol Reference\n\n### HTTP Request Structure\n```http\nGET /api/courses HTTP/1.1\nHost: api.rlearn.com\nAccept: application/json\nAuthorization: Bearer eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9...\nUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64)\nConnection: keep-alive\n```\n\n### HTTP Response Structure\n```http\nHTTP/1.1 200 OK\nContent-Type: application/json\nContent-Length: 1247\nCache-Control: max-age=3600\nX-Request-Id: a1b2c3d4\n\n{"courses": [{"id": 1, "title": "HTML5 Fundamentals"}]}\n```\n\n### DNS Record Types\n```\nA Record     → Maps domain to IPv4 address\n              rlearn.com → 104.21.45.67\n\nAAAA Record  → Maps domain to IPv6 address\nCNAME Record → Alias one domain to another\n              www.rlearn.com → rlearn.com\n\nMX Record    → Mail server address\nTXT Record   → Verification strings (Google, SPF)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Multiple Code Examples\n\n### Example 1 — Checking DNS with Command Line\n```bash\n# Windows\nnslookup google.com\n\n# Mac/Linux\ndig google.com\ndig +short google.com        # Just the IP\ndig google.com ANY           # All records\n\n# Output:\n# google.com. 300 IN A 142.250.80.46\n```\n\n### Example 2 — Making HTTP Requests with JavaScript\n```javascript\n// Basic fetch request\nconst response = await fetch("https://api.rlearn.com/courses");\nconst courses  = await response.json();\nconsole.log(courses);\n\n// Checking response headers\nconsole.log(response.status);           // 200\nconsole.log(response.headers.get("content-type")); // application/json\n\n// POST request\nconst result = await fetch("https://api.rlearn.com/enroll", {\n  method:  "POST",\n  headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },\n  body:    JSON.stringify({ courseId: "c1" }),\n});\n```\n\n### Example 3 — Measuring Network Performance\n```javascript\n// Use the Performance API to measure request time\nperformance.mark("start-fetch");\nconst response = await fetch("/api/data");\nperformance.mark("end-fetch");\nperformance.measure("fetch-time", "start-fetch", "end-fetch");\n\nconst [entry] = performance.getEntriesByName("fetch-time");\nconsole.log(`Fetch took: ${entry.duration.toFixed(2)}ms`);\n\n// Network timing breakdown\nconst [navEntry] = performance.getEntriesByType("navigation");\nconsole.log({\n  DNS:      navEntry.domainLookupEnd - navEntry.domainLookupStart,\n  TCP:      navEntry.connectEnd - navEntry.connectStart,\n  TLS:      navEntry.secureConnectionStart ? navEntry.connectEnd - navEntry.secureConnectionStart : 0,\n  TTFB:     navEntry.responseStart - navEntry.requestStart,\n  Download: navEntry.responseEnd - navEntry.responseStart,\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Try It Yourself\n\n### Exercise 1 — Network Inspector\n1. Open Chrome → Press **F12** (DevTools)\n2. Click the **Network** tab\n3. Visit `https://www.wikipedia.org`\n4. Answer:\n   - How many requests were made?\n   - What was the status code of the first HTML request?\n   - How long did DNS resolution take?\n   - What is the Content-Type of the main HTML file?\n\n### Exercise 2 — DNS Investigation\nOpen your terminal and run:\n```bash\nnslookup github.com\nnslookup api.github.com\n```\nQuestion: Are they on the same IP? Why or why not?\n\n### Exercise 3 — HTTP Headers Explorer\nIn browser DevTools → Network tab → Click any request → Headers tab.\nFind and write down:\n- The `Server` header value\n- The `Cache-Control` value\n- The response status code\n\n---\n\n## 8. Common Mistakes\n\n| Mistake | Why It Is Wrong | Correct Understanding |\n|---------|-----------------|----------------------|\n| "The internet and web are the same" | The web is just one service on the internet | Internet = infrastructure; Web = service |\n| "HTTPS is just HTTP with a lock icon" | TLS provides encryption, authentication, and integrity | HTTPS = HTTP + TLS handshake + certificate |\n| "DNS is just a phone book" | DNS also handles load balancing, CDN routing, and failover | DNS is a distributed, hierarchical, cached system |\n| "Websites are stored on my computer" | Pages are generated or stored on remote servers | You download them temporarily each visit |\n| "Faster internet = faster website" | Network is one factor; server processing, DB queries, rendering also matter | Website speed = network + server + code + browser |\n\n---\n\n## 9. Best Practices\n\n**For Developers:**\n- Always use HTTPS — never HTTP — for any production site\n- Minimize the number of HTTP requests (combine files, use sprites)\n- Use a CDN to serve static assets from servers close to users\n- Enable HTTP/2 — it multiplexes requests over one TCP connection\n- Add proper Cache-Control headers to reduce repeat downloads\n- Use lazy loading for images below the fold\n\n**For Performance:**\n```\nGood:  Static assets on CDN, gzipped responses, HTTP/2, keep-alive connections\nBad:   Uncompressed assets, blocking scripts in <head>, no caching headers\n```\n\n---\n\n## 10. Real-World Usage\n\n### At Flipkart / Amazon\nWhen millions of users shop during a sale, their engineering teams:\n- Use **CDNs** (CloudFront, Akamai) to serve images from edge servers\n- Pre-warm **DNS caches** to reduce lookup time\n- Enable **HTTP/2 push** to send CSS/JS before the browser asks\n- Monitor **TTFB** (Time to First Byte) and alert if > 200ms\n\n### At UPI / Razorpay\n- Every payment is an HTTPS POST request with encrypted body\n- TLS certificates are validated before any sensitive data is sent\n- TCP keepalive ensures the connection does not drop mid-transaction\n\n---\n\n## 11. Interview Preparation\n\n**Q1: What happens when you type a URL in a browser and press Enter?**\n> Answer: DNS lookup → TCP connection → TLS handshake (HTTPS) → HTTP request → Server processes → HTTP response → Browser renders HTML → CSS/JS loaded → Page displayed\n\n**Q2: What is the difference between HTTP and HTTPS?**\n> HTTP: Plaintext, no encryption, port 80. HTTPS: Encrypted via TLS, authenticated via certificate, port 443. All data in HTTPS is unreadable to anyone intercepting the traffic.\n\n**Q3: What is DNS and why is it important?**\n> DNS (Domain Name System) translates human-readable domain names (rlearn.com) into machine-readable IP addresses (104.21.45.67). Without DNS, users would need to memorize IP addresses to visit websites.\n\n**Q4: What is latency and how does it affect web performance?**\n> Latency is the delay in data traveling from source to destination. High latency = slow pages. Affected by physical distance, network congestion, server processing time, and number of round trips.\n\n**Q5: What is a CDN and why do companies use it?**\n> CDN (Content Delivery Network): A network of servers distributed globally that caches and serves static content from the server nearest to the user, reducing latency and server load.\n\n---\n\n## 12. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What does DNS stand for and what does it do?\n2. What is the difference between the internet and the World Wide Web?\n3. In a client-server model, which is your browser?\n4. What is the purpose of a TCP handshake?\n5. Why should websites always use HTTPS instead of HTTP?\n6. What is an IP address?\n7. What does TTFB stand for and why does it matter?\n8. How does a CDN improve website performance?\n9. What happens during the TLS handshake?\n10. Name three things that affect website loading speed besides internet speed.\n\n---\n\n## 13. Coding Challenges\n\n### Easy — HTTP Status Classifier\n```\nProblem: Write a function that takes an HTTP status code and returns its category.\n\nInput:  statusCode (number)\nOutput: string — "Informational" | "Success" | "Redirect" | "Client Error" | "Server Error"\n\nTest Cases:\nstatusClassifier(200) → "Success"\nstatusClassifier(404) → "Client Error"\nstatusClassifier(500) → "Server Error"\nstatusClassifier(301) → "Redirect"\nstatusClassifier(101) → "Informational"\n```\n\n```javascript\nfunction statusClassifier(code) {\n  if (code >= 100 && code < 200) return "Informational";\n  if (code >= 200 && code < 300) return "Success";\n  if (code >= 300 && code < 400) return "Redirect";\n  if (code >= 400 && code < 500) return "Client Error";\n  if (code >= 500 && code < 600) return "Server Error";\n  return "Unknown";\n}\n```\n\n### Medium — URL Parser\n```\nProblem: Parse a URL string into its components.\n\nInput:  "https://api.rlearn.com:8080/courses?category=frontend&page=2#results"\nOutput: {\n  protocol: "https",\n  host:     "api.rlearn.com",\n  port:     "8080",\n  path:     "/courses",\n  query:    { category: "frontend", page: "2" },\n  hash:     "results"\n}\n```\n\n```javascript\nfunction parseURL(url) {\n  const parsed = new URL(url);\n  return {\n    protocol: parsed.protocol.replace(":", ""),\n    host:     parsed.hostname,\n    port:     parsed.port,\n    path:     parsed.pathname,\n    query:    Object.fromEntries(parsed.searchParams),\n    hash:     parsed.hash.replace("#", ""),\n  };\n}\n```\n\n### Hard — Network Waterfall Analyzer\n```\nProblem: Given an array of network requests with start/end times,\nfind the critical path (longest chain where each request starts\nafter the previous one ends).\n\nInput:\n[\n  { id: 1, start: 0,   end: 100, deps: [] },\n  { id: 2, start: 100, end: 250, deps: [1] },\n  { id: 3, start: 50,  end: 150, deps: [] },\n  { id: 4, start: 250, end: 400, deps: [2] },\n]\n\nOutput: Critical path = [1, 2, 4], total duration = 400ms\n\nHint: This is a longest path in a DAG problem.\n```\n\n---\n\n## 14. Mini Project — Network Monitor Dashboard\n\nBuild a simple network performance monitor using the Performance API:\n\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang="en">\n<head>\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">\n  <title>Network Monitor</title>\n  <style>\n    body { font-family: Inter, sans-serif; padding: 2rem; background: #f8fafc; }\n    .metric { background: white; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 8px; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; }\n    .metric h3 { margin: 0 0 0.5rem; color: #3b82f6; }\n    .metric p  { margin: 0; font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: bold; }\n    .good  { border-left: 4px solid #10b981; }\n    .warn  { border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; }\n    .bad   { border-left: 4px solid #ef4444; }\n  </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n  <h1>Network Performance Monitor</h1>\n  <div id="metrics"></div>\n\n  <script>\n    window.addEventListener("load", () => {\n      const nav = performance.getEntriesByType("navigation")[0];\n\n      const metrics = [\n        { name: "DNS Lookup",    value: nav.domainLookupEnd - nav.domainLookupStart,   good: 10,  warn: 50  },\n        { name: "TCP Connect",   value: nav.connectEnd - nav.connectStart,             good: 20,  warn: 100 },\n        { name: "Time to First Byte (TTFB)", value: nav.responseStart - nav.requestStart, good: 100, warn: 300 },\n        { name: "Download Time", value: nav.responseEnd - nav.responseStart,           good: 100, warn: 500 },\n        { name: "DOM Processing",value: nav.domComplete - nav.domInteractive,          good: 200, warn: 1000 },\n        { name: "Total Load",    value: nav.loadEventEnd - nav.navigationStart,        good: 1000, warn: 3000 },\n      ];\n\n      const container = document.getElementById("metrics");\n      metrics.forEach(({ name, value, good, warn }) => {\n        const cls = value <= good ? "good" : value <= warn ? "warn" : "bad";\n        container.innerHTML += `\n          <div class="metric ${cls}">\n            <h3>${name}</h3>\n            <p>${value.toFixed(1)} ms</p>\n          </div>\n        `;\n      });\n    });\n  </script>\n</body>\n</html>\n```\n\n**Tasks:**\n1. Open the file in a browser and record the metrics\n2. Add a "Test URL" input that fetches a URL and measures its response time\n3. Add a history chart showing the last 10 measurements\n4. Add export to CSV functionality\n\n---\n\n## 15. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Takeaway |\n|---------|-------------|\n| Internet | Global network of connected computers |\n| World Wide Web | A service running on the internet (HTTP/HTTPS) |\n| Client-Server | Browser requests; server responds |\n| DNS | Translates domain names to IP addresses |\n| IP Address | Unique identifier for every device on a network |\n| TCP | Reliable transport protocol (guarantees delivery) |\n| HTTP | The request/response protocol of the web |\n| HTTPS | HTTP + TLS encryption — always use this |\n| CDN | Servers distributed globally to reduce latency |\n| Latency | Delay in data travel — affects page speed |\n\n**The journey of every web request:** You type URL → DNS lookup → TCP connect → TLS handshake → HTTP request → Server processes → HTTP response → Browser renders → You see the page.\n\nMastering this mental model will help you debug network issues, optimize performance, and design better systems throughout your career.', 15, 1)
