UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Clients, Servers & HTTP Protocol\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nHTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol) is the language browsers and servers use to communicate. Every web page you load, every API you call, every form you submit — all of it uses HTTP.\n\nAs a developer, understanding HTTP is like a doctor understanding anatomy. You cannot properly debug, optimize, or build web applications without knowing how HTTP requests and responses work.\n\n> **Real-World Context:** When a React app makes a fetch() call, or when Node.js handles a POST request, or when an API returns a 404 — all of these are HTTP in action. Companies like Stripe, GitHub, and Supabase build entire platforms on HTTP APIs.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this lesson you will be able to:\n- Explain the client-server architecture\n- List all HTTP methods and know when to use each\n- Read and interpret HTTP status codes\n- Understand HTTP headers (request and response)\n- Use browser DevTools to inspect real HTTP traffic\n- Explain the difference between HTTP/1.1, HTTP/2, and HTTP/3\n- Build and send custom HTTP requests\n\n---\n\n## 3. Concept Explanation\n\n### Beginner — What is HTTP?\n\nHTTP is a set of rules for how a client (browser) asks for things and how a server responds.\n\n```\nClient (Browser)         Server\n       |                    |\n       |-- REQUEST -------->|  "Give me the homepage"\n       |                    |\n       |<--- RESPONSE ------|  "Here is the HTML"\n       |                    |\n```\n\nEvery HTTP interaction has two parts:\n- **Request** — sent by the client\n- **Response** — sent by the server\n\n### Intermediate — HTTP Methods (Verbs)\n\n| Method | Purpose | Safe? | Idempotent? | Body? |\n|--------|---------|-------|-------------|-------|\n| GET | Read data | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ |\n| POST | Create resource | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |\n| PUT | Replace resource completely | ❌ | ✅ | ✅ |\n| PATCH | Update part of resource | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |\n| DELETE | Remove resource | ❌ | ✅ | ❌ |\n| HEAD | Get headers only (no body) | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ |\n| OPTIONS | Check allowed methods | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ |\n\n**Safe** = Does not modify data\n**Idempotent** = Multiple identical requests = same result as one request\n\n### Advanced — HTTP/1.1 vs HTTP/2 vs HTTP/3\n\n```\nHTTP/1.1 (1997-present)\n  - One request per TCP connection\n  - Head-of-line blocking (requests queue)\n  - Text-based headers (large overhead)\n  - Keep-alive connections help but not perfect\n\nHTTP/2 (2015-present)  ← Most websites today\n  - Multiple requests over ONE TCP connection (multiplexing)\n  - Binary protocol (faster parsing)\n  - Header compression (HPACK)\n  - Server Push (send assets before asked)\n  - Solves head-of-line blocking at HTTP layer\n\nHTTP/3 (2022-present)  ← Growing adoption\n  - Uses QUIC (UDP-based) instead of TCP\n  - Faster connection establishment (0-RTT)\n  - Better performance on unstable networks (mobile)\n  - True head-of-line blocking elimination\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Visual Learning\n\n```\nHTTP REQUEST Anatomy\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  Request Line                                │\n│  POST /api/courses HTTP/1.1                  │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  Headers                                     │\n│  Host: api.rlearn.com                        │\n│  Content-Type: application/json              │\n│  Authorization: Bearer eyJhbGci...           │\n│  Accept: application/json                    │\n│  Connection: keep-alive                      │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  [Empty Line]                                │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  Body (only for POST, PUT, PATCH)            │\n│  {"title":"New Course","difficulty":"Beginner"} │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\nHTTP RESPONSE Anatomy\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  Status Line                                 │\n│  HTTP/1.1 201 Created                        │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  Headers                                     │\n│  Content-Type: application/json              │\n│  Location: /api/courses/abc-123              │\n│  Date: Mon, 03 Jun 2026 10:00:00 GMT         │\n│  X-Request-Id: 7d3f9a2e                      │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  [Empty Line]                                │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  Body                                        │\n│  {"id":"abc-123","title":"New Course"}       │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n\nHTTP STATUS CODE MAP\n   100-199        200-299        300-399        400-499        500-599\n  Informational    Success        Redirect      Client Error   Server Error\n      101            200            301            400            500\n  (Switching)      (OK)        (Moved Perm)   (Bad Request)  (Server Err)\n                   201            302            401            502\n                 (Created)    (Found/Temp)  (Unauthorized)  (Bad Gateway)\n                   204            304            403            503\n               (No Content)  (Not Modified)   (Forbidden)  (Unavailable)\n                              307/308           404            504\n                             (Temp/Perm)     (Not Found)    (Timeout)\n                                               422\n                                           (Unprocessable)\n                                               429\n                                          (Too Many Reqs)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Syntax / Reference\n\n### Request Headers You Must Know\n```http\n# Authentication\nAuthorization: Bearer <jwt_token>\nAuthorization: Basic <base64(user:pass)>\nAPI-Key: sk_live_abc123\n\n# Content negotiation\nContent-Type: application/json          # What I''m sending\nAccept: application/json, text/html     # What I can receive\nAccept-Language: en-US, hi;q=0.9\nAccept-Encoding: gzip, br, deflate\n\n# Caching\nCache-Control: no-cache\nIf-None-Match: "abc123"                 # Conditional GET\nIf-Modified-Since: Mon, 01 Jan 2024 00:00:00 GMT\n\n# CORS\nOrigin: https://rlearn.com\n\n# Custom\nX-Request-ID: 7d3f9a2e-4f5b-6c7d-8e9f\nX-Client-Version: 2.1.0\n```\n\n### Response Headers You Must Know\n```http\n# Content\nContent-Type: application/json; charset=utf-8\nContent-Length: 1247\nContent-Encoding: gzip\n\n# Caching\nCache-Control: public, max-age=3600\nETag: "abc123"\nLast-Modified: Mon, 01 Jan 2024 12:00:00 GMT\nExpires: Mon, 03 Jun 2026 12:00:00 GMT\n\n# Security\nStrict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains\nX-Content-Type-Options: nosniff\nX-Frame-Options: DENY\nContent-Security-Policy: default-src ''self''\n\n# Location\nLocation: /api/courses/abc-123          # After 201 or 301\n\n# Rate limiting\nX-RateLimit-Limit: 100\nX-RateLimit-Remaining: 95\nX-RateLimit-Reset: 1704067200\n\n# CORS\nAccess-Control-Allow-Origin: https://rlearn.com\nAccess-Control-Allow-Methods: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Multiple Code Examples\n\n### Example 1 — Basic fetch (GET)\n```javascript\n// GET — Retrieve data\nasync function getCourses() {\n  const response = await fetch("https://api.rlearn.com/courses");\n\n  // Always check if response is ok!\n  if (!response.ok) {\n    throw new Error(`HTTP error: ${response.status} ${response.statusText}`);\n  }\n\n  const courses = await response.json();\n  return courses;\n}\n```\n\n### Example 2 — POST with headers and body\n```javascript\n// POST — Create new resource\nasync function createCourse(courseData) {\n  const response = await fetch("https://api.rlearn.com/courses", {\n    method: "POST",\n    headers: {\n      "Content-Type": "application/json",\n      "Authorization": `Bearer ${localStorage.getItem("token")}`,\n    },\n    body: JSON.stringify(courseData),\n  });\n\n  if (response.status === 201) {\n    const newCourse = await response.json();\n    console.log("Created:", newCourse);\n    console.log("Location:", response.headers.get("location"));\n    return newCourse;\n  } else if (response.status === 400) {\n    const error = await response.json();\n    throw new Error(`Validation failed: ${JSON.stringify(error.details)}`);\n  } else if (response.status === 401) {\n    throw new Error("Please log in first");\n  }\n}\n\n// Usage\ncreateourse({\n  title: "JavaScript ES6+",\n  difficulty: "Intermediate",\n  category: "Frontend",\n});\n```\n\n### Example 3 — All HTTP Methods in a REST API Client\n```javascript\nconst API_URL = "https://api.rlearn.com";\n\nconst headers = (token) => ({\n  "Content-Type": "application/json",\n  "Authorization": `Bearer ${token}`,\n});\n\n// Full CRUD operations\nconst api = {\n  // GET — Read all\n  getCourses:  (token) =>\n    fetch(`${API_URL}/courses`, { headers: headers(token) }),\n\n  // GET — Read one\n  getCourse:   (id, token) =>\n    fetch(`${API_URL}/courses/${id}`, { headers: headers(token) }),\n\n  // POST — Create\n  createCourse: (data, token) =>\n    fetch(`${API_URL}/courses`, { method: "POST", headers: headers(token), body: JSON.stringify(data) }),\n\n  // PUT — Full replace\n  replaceCourse: (id, data, token) =>\n    fetch(`${API_URL}/courses/${id}`, { method: "PUT", headers: headers(token), body: JSON.stringify(data) }),\n\n  // PATCH — Partial update\n  updateCourse:  (id, data, token) =>\n    fetch(`${API_URL}/courses/${id}`, { method: "PATCH", headers: headers(token), body: JSON.stringify(data) }),\n\n  // DELETE — Remove\n  deleteCourse:  (id, token) =>\n    fetch(`${API_URL}/courses/${id}`, { method: "DELETE", headers: headers(token) }),\n};\n```\n\n### Example 4 — Reading Response Headers\n```javascript\nconst response = await fetch("/api/data");\n\n// Read all headers\nfor (const [key, value] of response.headers) {\n  console.log(`${key}: ${value}`);\n}\n\n// Read specific headers\nconsole.log("Content-Type:", response.headers.get("content-type"));\nconsole.log("Rate Limit:",   response.headers.get("x-ratelimit-remaining"));\nconsole.log("Request ID:",   response.headers.get("x-request-id"));\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Try It Yourself\n\n### Exercise 1 — API Explorer\nUsing JSONPlaceholder (free test API):\n\n```javascript\n// Task 1: Fetch and display 5 posts\nconst posts = await fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts?_limit=5");\nconst data  = await posts.json();\nconsole.table(data);\n\n// Task 2: Create a new post (simulated)\nconst newPost = await fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts", {\n  method:  "POST",\n  headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },\n  body: JSON.stringify({\n    title:  "My First Post",\n    body:   "Learning HTTP is fun!",\n    userId: 1,\n  }),\n});\nconsole.log("Status:", newPost.status);       // Should be 201\nconsole.log("Created:", await newPost.json());\n```\n\n### Exercise 2 — DevTools Network Audit\n1. Open any website in Chrome\n2. Open DevTools → Network tab\n3. Reload the page\n4. Find a request and answer:\n   - What HTTP method was used?\n   - What was the status code?\n   - How long did it take?\n   - What Content-Type was returned?\n   - Was it served from cache? (look for "304" or "from disk cache")\n\n---\n\n## 8. Common Mistakes\n\n### Mistake 1 — Not checking response.ok\n```javascript\n// WRONG — This always runs even if server returns 404/500\nconst data = await (await fetch("/api/user")).json();\n\n// CORRECT\nconst response = await fetch("/api/user");\nif (!response.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}`);\nconst data = await response.json();\n```\n\n### Mistake 2 — Sending sensitive data in GET requests\n```javascript\n// WRONG — Password appears in URL/logs\nfetch("/api/login?email=alice@example.com&password=secret123");\n\n// CORRECT — Use POST with body\nfetch("/api/login", {\n  method: "POST",\n  body: JSON.stringify({ email: "alice@example.com", password: "secret123" }),\n});\n```\n\n### Mistake 3 — Wrong HTTP method for wrong action\n```javascript\n// WRONG — Using GET to delete data\nfetch("/api/users/123/delete");  // GET request deleting data!\n\n// CORRECT\nfetch("/api/users/123", { method: "DELETE" });\n```\n\n### Mistake 4 — Forgetting Content-Type header\n```javascript\n// WRONG — Server receives garbled data\nfetch("/api/data", {\n  method: "POST",\n  body: JSON.stringify({ name: "Alice" }),  // Content-Type missing!\n});\n\n// CORRECT\nfetch("/api/data", {\n  method: "POST",\n  headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },\n  body: JSON.stringify({ name: "Alice" }),\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. Best Practices\n\n1. **Always handle errors** — Check `response.ok`, catch network errors with try/catch\n2. **Use the correct HTTP method** — GET reads, POST creates, PUT replaces, PATCH updates, DELETE removes\n3. **Set proper Content-Type** — Always set when sending a body\n4. **Never expose secrets in URLs** — Passwords, tokens → always in headers or body\n5. **Return proper status codes** — 201 for created, 204 for deleted, 422 for validation errors\n6. **Add Location header on 201** — Tell client where to find the new resource\n7. **Use HTTPS everywhere** — Never send sensitive data over HTTP\n8. **Implement rate limiting** — Return 429 with Retry-After header\n\n---\n\n## 10. Real-World Usage\n\n### REST APIs at Scale\n- **GitHub API** — 500 million+ requests/day, all HTTP\n- **Stripe Payments** — Each charge is a POST to /charges\n- **Supabase** — Auto-generates REST API from your database schema\n- **Twilio** — SMS sent via HTTP POST to their API\n\n### Status Codes in Production\n```\nWhen Zomato''s server is down:    503 Service Unavailable\nWhen your session expires:       401 Unauthorized\nWhen you access admin panel:     403 Forbidden\nWhen a product is deleted:       404 Not Found\nWhen you order too many items:   422 Unprocessable Entity\n```\n\n---\n\n## 11. Interview Preparation\n\n**Q: What is the difference between PUT and PATCH?**\n> PUT replaces the entire resource. PATCH updates only the specified fields. If you PUT a user with only {name: "Alice"}, it replaces ALL other fields with null. PATCH only updates name.\n\n**Q: Why is GET idempotent but POST is not?**\n> GET just reads data — no matter how many times you call it, the result is the same and nothing changes. POST creates a new resource each time you call it, so calling it twice creates two resources.\n\n**Q: When would you use a 204 vs 200 response?**\n> 204 (No Content) when the operation succeeded but there is no body to return — like a DELETE or a PUT update. 200 (OK) when there IS content to return in the response body.\n\n**Q: What is CORS and how does it work?**\n> CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) is a browser security feature that blocks requests to a different domain than the page''s origin. The server opts in by adding Access-Control-Allow-Origin headers. Preflight OPTIONS requests check permissions before the actual request.\n\n---\n\n## 12. Knowledge Check\n\n1. Which HTTP method should you use to partially update a user profile?\n2. What status code means "the request was accepted and a new resource was created"?\n3. What is the difference between authentication (401) and authorization (403)?\n4. Why is GET safe but POST is not?\n5. What header tells the server what format you are sending?\n6. What does idempotent mean? Give an example of an idempotent HTTP method.\n7. Which HTTP version supports multiplexing?\n8. What does a 429 status code mean?\n9. Which header is used for JWT authentication?\n10. What is the purpose of the OPTIONS HTTP method?\n\n---\n\n## 13. Coding Challenges\n\n### Easy — HTTP Method Validator\n```\nProblem: Given a route description, return the correct HTTP method.\n"Create a new user"         → "POST"\n"Get all products"          → "GET"\n"Update user email"         → "PATCH"\n"Replace entire document"   → "PUT"\n"Remove a comment"          → "DELETE"\n```\n\n### Medium — API Response Builder\n```\nProblem: Build a function that creates proper HTTP response objects.\n\nInput:  buildResponse("created", { id: 1, name: "Alice" })\nOutput: {\n  status: 201,\n  statusText: "Created",\n  headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json", "Location": "/api/resources/1" },\n  body: { id: 1, name: "Alice" }\n}\n\nHandle: "ok", "created", "not-found", "unauthorized", "validation-error", "server-error"\n```\n\n### Hard — HTTP Request Rate Limiter\n```\nProblem: Implement a rate limiter that allows at most N requests\nper window seconds per client IP.\n\nclass RateLimiter {\n  constructor(maxRequests, windowSeconds) {}\n  isAllowed(clientIp) {}\n  getRemaining(clientIp) {}\n  getResetTime(clientIp) {}\n}\n\nconst limiter = new RateLimiter(5, 60);\nlimiter.isAllowed("192.168.1.1") // true (1st request)\nlimiter.isAllowed("192.168.1.1") // true (2nd)\n...\nlimiter.isAllowed("192.168.1.1") // false (6th — rate limited)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 14. Mini Project — HTTP Request Inspector\n\nBuild a developer tool that shows HTTP request/response details:\n\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang="en">\n<head>\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">\n  <title>HTTP Inspector</title>\n  <style>\n    * { box-sizing: border-box; font-family: monospace; }\n    body { margin: 0; background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; }\n    .container { max-width: 900px; margin: 2rem auto; padding: 1rem; }\n    h1 { color: #38bdf8; }\n    .input-row { display: flex; gap: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }\n    select, input, button { padding: 0.75rem; border-radius: 6px; border: 1px solid #475569; background: #0f172a; color: #e2e8f0; }\n    input { flex: 1; }\n    button { background: #3b82f6; color: white; cursor: pointer; border: none; }\n    .panel { background: #0f172a; border: 1px solid #334155; border-radius: 8px; padding: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }\n    .panel h3 { color: #94a3b8; margin-top: 0; }\n    .status-ok   { color: #10b981; }\n    .status-warn { color: #f59e0b; }\n    .status-err  { color: #ef4444; }\n    pre { white-space: pre-wrap; word-break: break-all; }\n  </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n  <div class="container">\n    <h1>HTTP Request Inspector</h1>\n\n    <div class="input-row">\n      <select id="method">\n        <option>GET</option><option>POST</option><option>PUT</option>\n        <option>PATCH</option><option>DELETE</option>\n      </select>\n      <input id="url" type="url" placeholder="https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/1" />\n      <button onclick="sendRequest()">Send</button>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class="panel" id="request-panel" style="display:none">\n      <h3>REQUEST</h3>\n      <pre id="request-display"></pre>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class="panel" id="response-panel" style="display:none">\n      <h3>RESPONSE <span id="status-display"></span>\n        <small id="time-display" style="color:#64748b"></small>\n      </h3>\n      <h4 style="color:#94a3b8">Headers</h4>\n      <pre id="headers-display"></pre>\n      <h4 style="color:#94a3b8">Body</h4>\n      <pre id="body-display"></pre>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <script>\n    async function sendRequest() {\n      const method = document.getElementById("method").value;\n      const url    = document.getElementById("url").value;\n      if (!url) { alert("Enter a URL"); return; }\n\n      document.getElementById("request-panel").style.display = "block";\n      document.getElementById("response-panel").style.display = "none";\n      document.getElementById("request-display").textContent =\n        `${method} ${url}\\nHeaders: {}\\nBody: (none)`;\n\n      const start = Date.now();\n      try {\n        const res  = await fetch(url, { method });\n        const time = Date.now() - start;\n        const body = await res.text();\n\n        let headerText = "";\n        for (const [k, v] of res.headers) headerText += `${k}: ${v}\\n`;\n\n        const statusEl = document.getElementById("status-display");\n        statusEl.textContent = `${res.status} ${res.statusText}`;\n        statusEl.className = res.ok ? "status-ok" : "status-err";\n\n        document.getElementById("time-display").textContent = `  ${time}ms`;\n        document.getElementById("headers-display").textContent = headerText;\n\n        try {\n          document.getElementById("body-display").textContent =\n            JSON.stringify(JSON.parse(body), null, 2);\n        } catch {\n          document.getElementById("body-display").textContent = body;\n        }\n\n        document.getElementById("response-panel").style.display = "block";\n      } catch (err) {\n        alert(`Error: ${err.message}`);\n      }\n    }\n  </script>\n</body>\n</html>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 15. Lesson Summary\n\n| Topic | Key Takeaway |\n|-------|-------------|\n| HTTP Methods | GET=read, POST=create, PUT=replace, PATCH=update, DELETE=remove |\n| Status Codes | 2xx=success, 3xx=redirect, 4xx=client error, 5xx=server error |\n| Headers | Metadata about request/response: auth, content-type, caching |\n| HTTP/2 | Multiplexing, binary, header compression — use it |\n| HTTPS | Always use in production — TLS encrypts everything |\n| response.ok | ALWAYS check before parsing the response body |\n| Idempotent | Same request, same result — GET/PUT/DELETE are idempotent |\n\nHTTP is the foundation of the entire web. Every framework, every API, every browser interaction uses it. Master HTTP and you master the language of the web.', 20, 2)
WHERE id = 'l10102';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Your First HTML Document — The Foundation of the Web\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nEvery webpage you have ever visited — from Facebook to Zomato to your bank — is built on HTML. HTML is the skeleton, the foundation, the structure that holds everything together.\n\nHTML stands for **HyperText Markup Language**. It is not a programming language — it is a markup language. You do not write logic in HTML. You write **structure**. You define what exists on a page and what role each element plays.\n\nThis lesson will teach you to write HTML from a blank file to a fully structured document — the way professional developers do it.\n\n> **Industry Context:** Every frontend engineer — whether they work in React, Angular, Vue, or plain JavaScript — must understand HTML deeply. React''s JSX, for instance, is just JavaScript that produces HTML. If you don''t understand HTML, you won''t understand JSX.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this lesson you will be able to:\n- Write a valid, complete HTML5 document from memory\n- Understand the role of every line in the boilerplate\n- Use essential meta tags for SEO, responsive design, and character encoding\n- Link external CSS and JavaScript correctly\n- Validate your HTML\n- Understand what the browser does with your HTML file\n\n---\n\n## 3. Concept Explanation\n\n### Beginner — What is HTML Markup?\n\nHTML uses **tags** to mark up text. Tags are wrapped in angle brackets:\n\n```html\n<h1>This is a heading</h1>\n<p>This is a paragraph</p>\n<a href="https://example.com">This is a link</a>\n```\n\nMost tags come in pairs: an **opening tag** `<p>` and a **closing tag** `</p>`.\n\nSome tags are **self-closing** (void elements):\n```html\n<img src="photo.jpg" alt="Photo">\n<br>\n<input type="text">\n<meta charset="UTF-8">\n```\n\n### Intermediate — The HTML5 Boilerplate Explained Line by Line\n\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang="en">\n<head>\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">\n  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">\n  <meta name="description" content="R-Learn — Professional Web Development Courses">\n  <meta name="author" content="R-Learn Team">\n  <title>R-Learn — Learn to Code</title>\n  <link rel="icon" type="image/png" href="/favicon.png">\n  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">\n</head>\n<body>\n  <h1>Welcome to R-Learn</h1>\n  <p>Your journey to becoming a professional developer starts here.</p>\n\n  <script src="app.js" defer></script>\n</body>\n</html>\n```\n\nEvery single line exists for a reason:\n\n| Line | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `<!DOCTYPE html>` | Tells browser: use HTML5 standards mode (not quirks mode) |\n| `<html lang="en">` | Root element; lang attribute helps screen readers and search engines |\n| `<head>` | Container for metadata — nothing visible goes here |\n| `charset="UTF-8"` | Supports all characters: English, Hindi, Arabic, emoji |\n| `name="viewport"` | Makes page responsive on mobile devices |\n| `name="description"` | Text Google shows in search results under the page title |\n| `<title>` | Text in browser tab; crucial for SEO |\n| `<link rel="icon">` | Favicon (the small icon in the browser tab) |\n| `<link rel="stylesheet">` | Links external CSS file |\n| `<body>` | All visible content goes here |\n| `<script defer>` | Loads JS after HTML is parsed (prevents blocking) |\n\n### Advanced — What Browsers Do With Your HTML\n\n```\nStep 1: HTML Parsing\n  Browser reads HTML top-to-bottom\n  Builds the DOM (Document Object Model)\n  DOM = JavaScript''s tree representation of your HTML\n\nStep 2: CSS Processing\n  Downloads and parses CSS files\n  Builds CSSOM (CSS Object Model)\n\nStep 3: Render Tree Construction\n  Combines DOM + CSSOM\n  Only visible elements included\n\nStep 4: Layout (Reflow)\n  Calculates exact position and size of each element\n  Expensive — avoid triggering it in JavaScript loops\n\nStep 5: Paint\n  Draws pixels to screen\n  Text, borders, backgrounds, shadows\n\nStep 6: Composite\n  Combines layers (GPU)\n  Transform and opacity changes happen here (fast!)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Visual Learning\n\n```\nHTML DOCUMENT TREE STRUCTURE\n\nDocument\n└── html (lang="en")\n    ├── head\n    │   ├── meta (charset="UTF-8")\n    │   ├── meta (name="viewport" ...)\n    │   ├── meta (name="description" ...)\n    │   ├── title\n    │   │   └── "R-Learn - Learn to Code"\n    │   └── link (rel="stylesheet")\n    └── body\n        ├── h1\n        │   └── "Welcome to R-Learn"\n        ├── p\n        │   └── "Your journey..."\n        └── script (defer)\n\n\nCRITICAL RENDERING PATH\n\n HTML File\n     ↓\n Browser Parser\n     ↓\n    DOM          CSS File\n     |               ↓\n     |          CSSOM\n     ↓              ↓\n  Render Tree (DOM + CSSOM)\n        ↓\n      Layout\n        ↓\n      Paint\n        ↓\n    Composite\n        ↓\n   User sees page\n\n\nSCRIPT LOADING COMPARISON\n\n Normal:    HTML parse → STOP → Download JS → Execute JS → Continue HTML\n defer:     HTML parse continues... download JS async... execute after parse done\n async:     HTML parse continues... download JS async... STOP → Execute → Continue\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Syntax Reference\n\n### HTML Boilerplate — Minimal\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang="en">\n<head>\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">\n  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">\n  <title>Page Title</title>\n</head>\n<body>\n  <!-- Your content here -->\n</body>\n</html>\n```\n\n### HTML Boilerplate — Production Ready\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang="en">\n<head>\n  <!-- Encoding (always first) -->\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">\n\n  <!-- Responsive design (always second) -->\n  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">\n\n  <!-- SEO Meta Tags -->\n  <meta name="description" content="Your page description (150-160 chars)">\n  <meta name="robots" content="index, follow">\n  <meta name="author" content="Company Name">\n\n  <!-- Open Graph (Social Media Sharing) -->\n  <meta property="og:title" content="Page Title">\n  <meta property="og:description" content="Page description">\n  <meta property="og:image" content="https://example.com/og-image.jpg">\n  <meta property="og:url" content="https://example.com/page">\n  <meta property="og:type" content="website">\n\n  <!-- Twitter Card -->\n  <meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image">\n  <meta name="twitter:title" content="Page Title">\n\n  <!-- Favicon -->\n  <link rel="icon" type="image/svg+xml" href="/favicon.svg">\n  <link rel="apple-touch-icon" href="/apple-touch-icon.png">\n\n  <!-- Preconnect to external domains (performance) -->\n  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com">\n  <link rel="dns-prefetch" href="https://cdn.example.com">\n\n  <!-- Canonical URL (prevents duplicate content) -->\n  <link rel="canonical" href="https://example.com/page">\n\n  <!-- CSS -->\n  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">\n\n  <!-- Page Title (50-60 characters for SEO) -->\n  <title>R-Learn — Professional Web Development Courses</title>\n</head>\n<body>\n\n  <!-- All visible content here -->\n\n  <!-- Scripts at bottom with defer -->\n  <script src="app.js" defer></script>\n</body>\n</html>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Multiple Code Examples\n\n### Example 1 — Personal Profile Page\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang="en">\n<head>\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">\n  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">\n  <title>Alice Sharma — Full Stack Developer</title>\n  <meta name="description" content="Alice Sharma is a Full Stack Developer specializing in React and Node.js">\n</head>\n<body>\n  <h1>Alice Sharma</h1>\n  <h2>Full Stack Developer</h2>\n  <p>Bengaluru, India | alice@example.com</p>\n\n  <h3>About Me</h3>\n  <p>3+ years of experience building scalable web applications using React, Node.js, and PostgreSQL.</p>\n\n  <h3>Skills</h3>\n  <p>JavaScript, TypeScript, React, Node.js, PostgreSQL, Docker</p>\n\n  <h3>Experience</h3>\n  <p><strong>Senior Frontend Developer</strong> — TechCorp India (2022-present)</p>\n  <p>Built the customer dashboard serving 500K daily active users.</p>\n</body>\n</html>\n```\n\n### Example 2 — Course Landing Page\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang="en">\n<head>\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">\n  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">\n  <title>HTML5 Fundamentals — R-Learn</title>\n  <meta name="description" content="Learn HTML5 from scratch. 12 modules, 40+ lessons, hands-on projects.">\n  <meta property="og:title" content="HTML5 Fundamentals — R-Learn">\n  <meta property="og:image" content="https://rlearn.com/images/html5-course.jpg">\n  <link rel="stylesheet" href="course.css">\n</head>\n<body>\n  <header>\n    <h1>HTML5 Fundamentals</h1>\n    <p>Master the building blocks of the web</p>\n  </header>\n\n  <main>\n    <section>\n      <h2>What You Will Learn</h2>\n      <p>Document structure, semantic elements, forms, accessibility, and more.</p>\n    </section>\n\n    <section>\n      <h2>Course Details</h2>\n      <p>12 hours · Beginner · 40+ lessons · Certificate on completion</p>\n    </section>\n  </main>\n\n  <footer>\n    <p>&copy; 2026 R-Learn. All rights reserved.</p>\n  </footer>\n\n  <script src="course.js" defer></script>\n</body>\n</html>\n```\n\n### Example 3 — Multi-language Site Setup\n```html\n<!-- English version -->\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang="en">\n<head>\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">\n  <title>R-Learn</title>\n  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="hi" href="https://rlearn.com/hi/">\n  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="en" href="https://rlearn.com/">\n</head>\n<body>...</body>\n</html>\n\n<!-- Hindi version -->\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang="hi">\n<head>\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">\n  <title>आर-लर्न</title>\n</head>\n<body>...</body>\n</html>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Try It Yourself\n\n### Exercise 1 — Build From Memory\nWithout looking at notes, write the complete HTML5 boilerplate. Include:\n- DOCTYPE\n- html with lang attribute\n- head with: charset, viewport, description, title\n- body with an h1, two paragraphs\n- A script tag with defer at the bottom\n\n### Exercise 2 — Profile Page\nCreate a profile page for yourself with:\n- Your name as h1\n- Your role as h2\n- A short bio as paragraph\n- A section with your skills\n- Your email as a mailto link\n- Link to an external CSS file (even if empty)\n\n### Exercise 3 — Add Open Graph Tags\nTake your profile page and add Open Graph meta tags so it looks good when shared on LinkedIn:\n- og:title\n- og:description\n- og:image (use any image URL)\n- og:url\n- og:type\n\nTest using the LinkedIn Post Inspector at: https://www.linkedin.com/post-inspector/\n\n---\n\n## 8. Common Mistakes\n\n### Mistake 1 — Missing DOCTYPE\n```html\n<!-- WRONG — Triggers "quirks mode" in browsers -->\n<html>\n<head>...</head>\n<body>...</body>\n</html>\n\n<!-- CORRECT -->\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang="en">\n...\n</html>\n```\n\n### Mistake 2 — Script blocking in head\n```html\n<!-- WRONG — JS blocks HTML parsing -->\n<head>\n  <script src="app.js"></script>  <!-- ← blocks everything below! -->\n</head>\n\n<!-- CORRECT — Use defer or place at bottom -->\n<head>...\n</head>\n<body>\n  ...\n  <script src="app.js" defer></script>\n</body>\n```\n\n### Mistake 3 — Missing viewport meta tag\n```html\n<!-- WRONG — Mobile users see tiny zoomed-out page -->\n<head>\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">\n  <title>My Site</title>\n  <!-- No viewport! -->\n</head>\n\n<!-- CORRECT -->\n<head>\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">\n  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">\n  <title>My Site</title>\n</head>\n```\n\n### Mistake 4 — Wrong charset placement\n```html\n<!-- WRONG — Must be first in head -->\n<head>\n  <title>My Site</title>            <!-- title before charset! -->\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">           <!-- too late -->\n</head>\n\n<!-- CORRECT -->\n<head>\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">           <!-- Always first -->\n  <title>My Site</title>\n</head>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. Best Practices\n\n1. **`charset="UTF-8"` must be the first meta tag** — before even the title\n2. **Viewport meta is required for mobile** — without it, responsive CSS is ignored\n3. **Title tag: 50-60 characters** — Google truncates longer titles in search results\n4. **Description: 150-160 characters** — Longer is truncated; shorter looks incomplete\n5. **Use `defer` on all scripts** — Never block HTML parsing with scripts\n6. **CSS in head, JS at bottom** — CSS must load before content displays; JS usually runs after\n7. **One `<h1>` per page** — Multiple h1s confuse search engines and screen readers\n8. **Set the `lang` attribute** — Screen readers use it to choose the right pronunciation engine\n\n---\n\n## 10. Real-World Usage\n\n### How Companies Set Up HTML\n\n**At startups:** Often use a single `index.html` as the entry point to a React/Vue SPA, with only the meta tags and root div.\n\n**At e-commerce companies:** Generate HTML dynamically on the server with per-page meta tags (different title and description for each product page) for SEO.\n\n**At media companies:** Use server-side rendering (Next.js) so the HTML arrives pre-filled with content for faster rendering and better SEO.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Interview Preparation\n\n**Q: What does `<!DOCTYPE html>` do?**\n> It tells the browser to use standards mode for HTML5. Without it, browsers use quirks mode which emulates old browser behavior and can cause layout bugs.\n\n**Q: Why put CSS in the head and JS at the bottom?**\n> CSS must be in the head because the browser needs styles before rendering (without CSS, the page flashes unstyled content). JS goes at the bottom (or uses defer) because it can block HTML parsing if placed in the head.\n\n**Q: What is the viewport meta tag and why is it essential?**\n> It tells the browser to use the device''s actual width for layout instead of a virtual desktop viewport. Without it, mobile browsers zoom out to fit a 980px-wide page, making responsive CSS useless.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `async` and `defer` on a script tag?**\n> `async` downloads the script asynchronously but executes it as soon as it downloads (possibly interrupting HTML parsing). `defer` downloads asynchronously but always executes after HTML is fully parsed. For most scripts, `defer` is safer.\n\n---\n\n## 12. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What does `<!DOCTYPE html>` tell the browser?\n2. What is the first meta tag that should appear inside `<head>`?\n3. Why is the viewport meta tag essential for mobile users?\n4. What is the difference between `<head>` and `<body>`?\n5. How does `defer` affect script loading?\n6. What does the `lang` attribute on `<html>` do?\n7. What should the `<title>` tag contain and how long should it be?\n8. Where should you link CSS files? Where should you link JS files?\n9. What happens if you omit `charset="UTF-8"` on a page with Hindi text?\n10. What is the purpose of Open Graph meta tags?\n\n---\n\n## 13. Coding Challenges\n\n### Easy — Boilerplate Generator\n```\nProblem: Write a JavaScript function that generates a complete HTML boilerplate.\n\nInput:  generateHTML({ title: "My Page", description: "My desc", author: "Alice" })\nOutput: A complete HTML string with proper structure, all meta tags, title, and empty body\n```\n\n### Medium — Meta Tag Extractor\n```\nProblem: Given an HTML string, extract all meta tag name/property-value pairs.\n\nInput: An HTML string\nOutput: An object like:\n{\n  charset: "UTF-8",\n  viewport: "width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0",\n  description: "Page description",\n  "og:title": "OpenGraph Title"\n}\n```\n\n### Hard — HTML Validator\n```\nProblem: Write a function that validates an HTML document and returns a list\nof errors/warnings similar to the W3C Validator.\n\nChecks:\n- Missing DOCTYPE\n- Missing charset\n- Missing viewport\n- Missing title\n- title length > 60 characters\n- Multiple h1 elements\n- Images without alt attribute\n- Script in head without defer/async\n\nInput:  HTML string\nOutput: Array of { severity, message, line } objects\n```\n\n---\n\n## 14. Mini Project — Personal Portfolio Page\n\nBuild a complete personal portfolio using only HTML (no CSS yet):\n\n**Requirements:**\n1. Proper HTML5 boilerplate with all meta tags\n2. Open Graph tags for LinkedIn sharing\n3. A header with your name (h1) and role (h2)\n4. A navigation with links: About, Skills, Projects, Contact\n5. An About section\n6. A Skills section with your top 5 skills\n7. A Projects section with 2-3 projects (title, description, link)\n8. A Contact section with email link and LinkedIn\n9. A footer with copyright\n10. A linked (but empty) CSS file\n11. A linked JS file with defer\n\n**Validate it:**\nPaste your HTML at https://validator.w3.org/#validate_by_input and fix all errors.\n\n---\n\n## 15. Lesson Summary\n\n| Element | Role | Must Know |\n|---------|------|----------|\n| `<!DOCTYPE html>` | Standards mode declaration | Write it first, always |\n| `<html lang="en">` | Root element with language | Set the correct language |\n| `<head>` | Metadata container | Nothing visible here |\n| `charset="UTF-8"` | Character encoding | First meta tag, always |\n| `name="viewport"` | Mobile responsiveness | Required for mobile |\n| `<title>` | Tab/search result text | 50-60 chars, unique per page |\n| `<body>` | Visible content | All user-facing content here |\n| `defer` | Non-blocking script | Use on all external scripts |\n\nA correct, complete HTML document is not optional — it is the foundation. Every mistake in the boilerplate can cause issues that are hard to debug: broken rendering on mobile, garbled text, poor SEO, or slow page loads. Write it correctly from the start.', 20, 1)
WHERE id = 'l10201';

-- Track 1 remaining lessons get solid comprehensive updates too
UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# HTML Tags & Attributes — The Building Blocks\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nIf HTML is a language, then **tags are the words** and **attributes are the adjectives**. Every element you see on a webpage — a button, an image, a form, a paragraph — is defined by tags and customized by attributes.\n\nMastering tags and attributes means you can build ANY interface using HTML.\n\n> **Reality Check:** Professional developers write HTML with tags and attributes every single day. Even in React, every JSX element compiles down to HTML tags. Understanding the underlying HTML is not optional.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\nBy end of lesson:\n- Write any HTML element using correct syntax\n- Use boolean, string, and data attributes\n- Know all global attributes\n- Apply ARIA attributes for accessibility\n- Avoid common tag/attribute mistakes\n- Understand void elements vs container elements\n\n---\n\n## 3. Concept Explanation\n\n### Beginner — Tag Syntax\n\n```html\n<!-- Container element: has opening AND closing tag -->\n<tagname attribute="value">Content inside</tagname>\n\n<!-- Void element: self-closing, cannot have children -->\n<tagname attribute="value">\n```\n\n**Anatomy of an element:**\n```\n<a href="https://rlearn.com" target="_blank" class="nav-link">\n│  │    │                    │              │\n│  │    │                    │              └─ Attribute (name + value)\n│  │    │                    └─ Attribute (name + value)\n│  │    └─ Attribute value\n│  └─ Attribute name\n└─ Tag name (opening)\n```\n\n### Intermediate — Attribute Types\n\n**1. String Attributes** (name="value")\n```html\n<a href="https://example.com">Link</a>\n<img src="/images/logo.png" alt="R-Learn Logo">\n<input type="email" placeholder="Enter your email">\n<div class="container main-wrapper">\n<p id="intro-paragraph">\n```\n\n**2. Boolean Attributes** (presence = true, absence = false)\n```html\n<!-- These are ALL equivalent -->\n<input type="checkbox" checked>\n<input type="checkbox" checked="">\n<input type="checkbox" checked="checked">\n\n<!-- Other boolean attributes -->\n<button disabled>Cannot click</button>\n<input type="text" required>\n<input type="text" readonly>\n<video controls autoplay muted loop>\n<details open>\n<select multiple>\n```\n\n**3. Data Attributes** (custom data for JavaScript)\n```html\n<div\n  data-user-id="123"\n  data-user-role="admin"\n  data-course-id="c-html5"\n  data-enrolled="true"\n>\n  Alice (Admin)\n</div>\n\n<!-- Access in JavaScript -->\n<script>\n  const el = document.querySelector("div");\n  console.log(el.dataset.userId);   // "123"\n  console.log(el.dataset.userRole); // "admin" (camelCase from data-user-role)\n  console.log(el.dataset.courseId); // "c-html5"\n</script>\n```\n\n**4. Event Attributes** (inline handlers — avoid in modern development)\n```html\n<!-- Avoid in modern code — but understand these exist -->\n<button onclick="handleClick()">Click</button>\n<form onsubmit="validate(event)">...</form>\n<input oninput="handleInput(this.value)">\n```\n\n### Advanced — ARIA Attributes for Accessibility\n\n```html\n<!-- Role: Tells screen readers what an element IS -->\n<div role="navigation" aria-label="Main navigation">\n<div role="main">\n<div role="dialog" aria-modal="true" aria-labelledby="dialog-title">\n<div role="alert">Error: Invalid email address</div>\n<div role="progressbar" aria-valuenow="65" aria-valuemin="0" aria-valuemax="100">\n\n<!-- Labels: Name elements for screen readers -->\n<button aria-label="Close dialog">×</button>\n<input id="search" aria-describedby="search-hint">\n<p id="search-hint">Search by course title or technology</p>\n\n<!-- State: Dynamic states for interactive components -->\n<button aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="menu-list">Menu</button>\n<ul id="menu-list" aria-hidden="true">...</ul>\n\n<input type="checkbox" aria-checked="true">\n<div aria-busy="true">Loading...</div>\n<div aria-live="polite">Dynamic content here updates automatically</div>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Visual Learning\n\n```\nHIERARCHY OF ATTRIBUTES\n\nAll HTML Attributes\n├── Global Attributes (work on ANY element)\n│   ├── id              → Unique identifier on page\n│   ├── class           → One or more CSS class names\n│   ├── style           → Inline CSS styles\n│   ├── title           → Tooltip text\n│   ├── lang            → Language of element content\n│   ├── dir             → Text direction (ltr/rtl)\n│   ├── hidden          → Hides element\n│   ├── tabindex        → Keyboard navigation order\n│   ├── contenteditable → Makes element editable\n│   ├── draggable       → Enables drag-and-drop\n│   ├── data-*          → Custom data storage\n│   └── aria-*          → Accessibility labels\n│\n├── Element-Specific Attributes\n│   ├── <a>    href, target, rel, download\n│   ├── <img>  src, alt, width, height, loading, decoding\n│   ├── <input> type, name, value, placeholder, required, disabled, readonly\n│   ├── <form> action, method, enctype, novalidate\n│   └── <link> rel, href, type, media\n│\n└── Event Attributes (onclick, onsubmit, etc.) — avoid\n\n\nNESTING RULES\n\nCORRECT nesting:\n<p>\n  This is <strong>bold</strong> and <em>italic</em> text.\n  <a href="#">A link</a> inside a paragraph.\n</p>\n\nWRONG nesting:\n<p>\n  <div>DIV inside P is invalid</div>  ← Block inside inline!\n</p>\n\n<a href="#">\n  <a href="#">Nested links are invalid</a>  ← a inside a!\n</a>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Syntax Reference — Complete Attribute Guide\n\n### Global Attributes\n```html\n<!-- id — unique per page -->\n<section id="about-us">...</section>\n<h2 id="course-heading">Courses</h2>\n\n<!-- class — multiple allowed, space-separated -->\n<div class="card featured highlighted">...</div>\n<button class="btn btn-primary btn-large">Enroll</button>\n\n<!-- style — inline CSS (avoid for large styles) -->\n<p style="color: red; font-size: 18px;">Warning text</p>\n\n<!-- title — tooltip on hover -->\n<abbr title="HyperText Markup Language">HTML</abbr>\n<button title="Delete this course permanently">Delete</button>\n\n<!-- hidden — removes element from display AND accessibility tree -->\n<div hidden>This is not visible</div>\n<span hidden id="error-msg">Email is invalid</span>\n\n<!-- tabindex -->\n<div tabindex="0">Focusable with Tab key (natural order)</div>\n<div tabindex="-1">Focusable via JavaScript only</div>\n<div tabindex="1">First in tab order (avoid — breaks natural flow)</div>\n\n<!-- contenteditable -->\n<div contenteditable="true">User can type here</div>\n\n<!-- data-* attributes -->\n<li data-product-id="P123" data-price="999" data-in-stock="true">\n  Product Name\n</li>\n\n<!-- lang -->\n<span lang="hi">नमस्ते</span>\n<span lang="ar" dir="rtl">مرحبا</span>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Multiple Code Examples\n\n### Example 1 — Anchor Tags: All Variations\n```html\n<!-- External link (opens in new tab) -->\n<a href="https://github.com/rlearn" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">\n  View on GitHub\n</a>\n\n<!-- Internal link -->\n<a href="/courses">Browse Courses</a>\n<a href="/courses#frontend">Frontend Courses</a>\n\n<!-- Same-page anchor -->\n<a href="#contact-section">Jump to Contact</a>\n<section id="contact-section">...</section>\n\n<!-- Email link -->\n<a href="mailto:support@rlearn.com?subject=Help&body=Hello">Email Support</a>\n\n<!-- Phone link -->\n<a href="tel:+917012345678">Call Us</a>\n\n<!-- Download link -->\n<a href="/certificates/html5.pdf" download="my-certificate.pdf">Download Certificate</a>\n\n<!-- Link with image inside -->\n<a href="/courses/html5">\n  <img src="html5-course.jpg" alt="HTML5 Fundamentals Course Cover">\n</a>\n```\n\n### Example 2 — Images: Correct Usage\n```html\n<!-- Basic image with required alt -->\n<img src="/images/course-html5.jpg" alt="HTML5 Fundamentals course thumbnail">\n\n<!-- Responsive image (specify dimensions to prevent CLS) -->\n<img\n  src="/images/hero.jpg"\n  alt="Developer working on laptop in a bright office"\n  width="1200"\n  height="600"\n  loading="lazy"\n  decoding="async"\n>\n\n<!-- Modern formats with fallback -->\n<picture>\n  <source srcset="/images/hero.avif" type="image/avif">\n  <source srcset="/images/hero.webp" type="image/webp">\n  <img src="/images/hero.jpg" alt="Hero image" width="1200" height="600">\n</picture>\n\n<!-- Decorative image (empty alt = screen reader ignores it) -->\n<img src="/images/decorative-swirl.svg" alt="">\n\n<!-- Responsive srcset -->\n<img\n  src="/images/photo-800.jpg"\n  srcset="\n    /images/photo-400.jpg 400w,\n    /images/photo-800.jpg 800w,\n    /images/photo-1600.jpg 1600w\n  "\n  sizes="(max-width: 600px) 400px, (max-width: 1200px) 800px, 1600px"\n  alt="Team photo"\n>\n```\n\n### Example 3 — Forms: Correct Attribute Usage\n```html\n<form action="/api/login" method="POST" novalidate>\n\n  <label for="email">Email Address <span aria-hidden="true">*</span></label>\n  <input\n    type="email"\n    id="email"\n    name="email"\n    placeholder="alice@example.com"\n    required\n    autocomplete="email"\n    aria-required="true"\n    aria-describedby="email-error"\n  >\n  <span id="email-error" role="alert" hidden>Please enter a valid email</span>\n\n  <label for="password">Password</label>\n  <input\n    type="password"\n    id="password"\n    name="password"\n    minlength="8"\n    required\n    autocomplete="current-password"\n  >\n\n  <button type="submit">Sign In</button>\n  <button type="reset">Clear</button>\n\n</form>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Try It Yourself\n\n### Exercise 1 — Build a Navigation\n```\nTask: Create a navigation bar with:\n- Logo (image linked to homepage)\n- 4 text links: Home, Courses, Challenges, Profile\n- A "Sign In" button styled differently\n- Links use correct rel attribute for external links\n```\n\n### Exercise 2 — Product Card\n```\nTask: Create a course card with:\n- Course thumbnail image (with alt, width, height, loading="lazy")\n- Course title in h3\n- Category badge span with data-category attribute\n- Duration, difficulty as paragraphs\n- An "Enroll Now" button with data-course-id attribute\n- The entire card title area linked to the course page\n```\n\n### Exercise 3 — Interactive Counter\n```html\n<!-- Build this interface using only HTML attributes (no CSS or JS yet): -->\n<div id="counter" data-count="0" data-min="0" data-max="10">\n  <button onclick="decrement()" aria-label="Decrease count">-</button>\n  <output id="count-display">0</output>\n  <button onclick="increment()" aria-label="Increase count">+</button>\n</div>\n\n<script>\n  function increment() {\n    const el  = document.getElementById("counter");\n    let count = parseInt(el.dataset.count);\n    const max = parseInt(el.dataset.max);\n    if (count < max) {\n      el.dataset.count = ++count;\n      document.getElementById("count-display").textContent = count;\n    }\n  }\n  function decrement() {\n    const el  = document.getElementById("counter");\n    let count = parseInt(el.dataset.count);\n    const min = parseInt(el.dataset.min);\n    if (count > min) {\n      el.dataset.count = --count;\n      document.getElementById("count-display").textContent = count;\n    }\n  }\n</script>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Common Mistakes\n\n### Mistake 1 — Missing alt on images\n```html\n<!-- WRONG — Screen reader: "image" (useless) -->\n<img src="logo.png">\n\n<!-- CORRECT -->\n<img src="logo.png" alt="R-Learn platform logo">\n\n<!-- Decorative: intentionally empty alt -->\n<img src="divider.svg" alt="">\n```\n\n### Mistake 2 — Duplicate IDs\n```html\n<!-- WRONG — ID must be unique on the page -->\n<section id="intro">...</section>\n<section id="intro">...</section>  <!-- Duplicate! -->\n\n<!-- CORRECT — use class for non-unique styles -->\n<section id="about-intro">...</section>\n<section id="courses-intro">...</section>\n```\n\n### Mistake 3 — Incorrect nesting\n```html\n<!-- WRONG — block element inside inline element -->\n<span>\n  <div>Cannot put div inside span</div>\n</span>\n\n<!-- WRONG — p cannot contain block elements -->\n<p>\n  <ul><li>Cannot have ul inside p</li></ul>\n</p>\n\n<!-- CORRECT -->\n<div>\n  <p>Paragraph inside div is fine</p>\n  <ul><li>List inside div is fine</li></ul>\n</div>\n```\n\n### Mistake 4 — Missing rel on external links\n```html\n<!-- WRONG — security vulnerability -->\n<a href="https://evil.com" target="_blank">External Link</a>\n<!-- target="_blank" gives the external page access to window.opener -->\n\n<!-- CORRECT -->\n<a href="https://evil.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">External Link</a>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. Best Practices\n\n1. **Always quote attribute values** — `class="nav-link"` not `class=nav-link`\n2. **Use lowercase tag names** — HTML5 is case-insensitive but lowercase is standard\n3. **Use meaningful IDs and classes** — `id="user-profile"` not `id="div3"`\n4. **Add alt to all non-decorative images** — Required for accessibility and SEO\n5. **Use data attributes for JavaScript** — Do not use ID/class for JS hooks\n6. **Add rel="noopener noreferrer"** on all `target="_blank"` links\n7. **Use ARIA only when semantic HTML is not enough** — `<button>` is better than `<div role="button">`\n\n---\n\n## 10. Real-World Usage\n\n### Data Attributes in Production\nAt e-commerce companies, product cards use data attributes:\n```html\n<div\n  class="product-card"\n  data-product-id="SKU-789"\n  data-category="electronics"\n  data-price="29999"\n  data-in-stock="true"\n  data-rating="4.2"\n>\n  ...\n</div>\n```\nJavaScript reads these to filter, sort, and add to cart without re-fetching from the API.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What are void elements? Give 5 examples.**\n> Void elements cannot have child content and do not have a closing tag. Examples: `<img>`, `<input>`, `<br>`, `<hr>`, `<meta>`, `<link>`, `<area>`, `<col>`, `<embed>`, `<source>`, `<wbr>`.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between an attribute and a property?**\n> Attributes are defined in HTML: `<input type="checkbox" checked>`. Properties are the JavaScript DOM properties: `inputEl.checked`. They are often the same but not always — the `href` attribute stores the raw string while `el.href` returns the full resolved URL.\n\n**Q: Why use `data-*` attributes instead of storing data in `id` or `class`?**\n> `id` and `class` are for identification and styling. `data-*` is designed for custom application data. Using data attributes keeps concerns separate and avoids conflicts with CSS classes.\n\n---\n\n## 12. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What is the difference between void elements and container elements?\n2. How do you make a checkbox checked by default in HTML?\n3. What does `rel="noopener noreferrer"` do on an anchor tag?\n4. How do you store custom data on an HTML element?\n5. What is the `tabindex` attribute used for?\n6. When should you use an empty `alt=""` attribute on an image?\n7. Can you put a `<div>` inside a `<span>`? Why or why not?\n8. What ARIA attribute announces dynamic content changes to screen readers?\n9. What is `contenteditable` used for?\n10. What is the difference between `disabled` and `readonly` on an input?\n\n---\n\n## 13. Coding Challenges\n\n### Easy — Attribute Parser\n```\nProblem: Parse an HTML tag string and extract all attributes as an object.\n\nparseAttributes(''<img src="/logo.png" alt="Logo" loading="lazy" width="200">'')\n→ { src: "/logo.png", alt: "Logo", loading: "lazy", width: "200" }\n\nparseAttributes(''<input type="checkbox" checked disabled name="agree">'')\n→ { type: "checkbox", checked: true, disabled: true, name: "agree" }\n```\n\n### Medium — Accessibility Auditor\n```\nProblem: Given an HTML string, find all accessibility issues:\n- img without alt attribute\n- button with no text content or aria-label\n- form input without associated label\n- links with text "click here" or "read more"\n- Missing lang attribute on html element\n\nInput:  HTML string\nOutput: Array of { issue, element, recommendation }\n```\n\n### Hard — HTML Sanitizer\n```\nProblem: Write a function that safely strips dangerous attributes from HTML\nwhile preserving safe structure (for rendering user-generated content).\n\nAllow: href, src, alt, class, id, title, width, height\nBlock: onclick, onmouseover, style (with javascript:), data-* with eval, etc.\nAlso block: javascript: in href/src values\n\nInput:  Potentially dangerous HTML string\nOutput: Safe HTML string\n\nTest:\nsanitize(''<a href="javascript:alert(1)">Click</a>'')\n→ ''<a>Click</a>''\n\nsanitize(''<img src="/safe.jpg" alt="Safe" onclick="evil()">'') \n→ ''<img src="/safe.jpg" alt="Safe">''\n```\n\n---\n\n## 14. Mini Project — Component Library Card\n\nBuild a reusable course card component in pure HTML:\n\n```html\n<!-- Build a card that shows this information: -->\n<!-- - Course thumbnail image with proper attributes -->\n<!-- - Category badge (Frontend / Backend / DevOps) with data-category -->\n<!-- - Course title as h3 -->\n<!-- - Instructor name with profile image -->\n<!-- - Stats: duration, lessons, enrolled count -->\n<!-- - Difficulty indicator (dots or stars) -->\n<!-- - Progress bar for enrolled users (using data-progress) -->\n<!-- - CTA button with data-course-id -->\n<!-- - Properly linked title to course page -->\n<!-- All interactive elements must be keyboard accessible -->\n<!-- All images must have alt text -->\n<!-- All buttons must have meaningful labels -->\n```\n\n---\n\n## 15. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Quick Reference |\n|---------|----------------|\n| Void elements | No closing tag: img, input, br, hr, meta, link |\n| String attributes | name="value" — most attributes |\n| Boolean attributes | Presence = true: checked, disabled, required, readonly |\n| Data attributes | data-* for custom JS data; access via el.dataset |\n| Global attributes | id, class, style, title, hidden, tabindex, lang, data-*, aria-* |\n| ARIA | Accessibility: role, aria-label, aria-hidden, aria-expanded |\n| Alt text | Required on all meaningful images; empty for decorative |\n| rel="noopener" | Required on all target="_blank" links (security) |\n\nTags are the vocabulary of HTML; attributes are the grammar. Together they define every element on every web page. Master these, and you can build any UI structure.', 15, 2)
